Argument:

Defendant's message (Exh. A) alleges that on or about 20 April 1996,
the Regulations of Morendil's Feline Orphanage were amended solely by
the deletion of the four so-called "temporary" regulations.  It has
recently been revealed that Defendant was less than truthful in this
disclosure; the Ordinances were also amended at the same time to
include another Ordinance, known as the Immaculate Ordinance (Exh. B).

It can be argued that Defendant's message does not specifically claim
that the reported changes are all the changes.  Petitioner disputes
this argument.  Had Defendant made no statement at all about what the
nature of the changes were, or if eir statement had been clearly vague
or incomplete, Petitioner would agree that it would not be reasonable
to assume that Defendant's statement did not completely represent the
nature of the changes to the Regulations.  However, Defendant's
statement appears to be a complete representation of the changes made,
and Petitioner suspects most reasonable people would believe that it
was a complete representation of the changes.  Therefore, Defendant
knew or should have reasonable know that the effect of eir message was
to import that the only change to the Regulations was the
aforementioned deletion, when in fact there were other changes.  Thus
eir message misrepresented the truth of the matter.  The emoticon at
the end of Defendant's message lends support to the principle that
Defendant expected his message to be misinterpreted as a complete
representation; this also establishes intent to misrepresent by
omission.  Both a later message from Defendant in response to
Petitioner's interrogatory (Exh. C) and another discussionary message
from Defendant suggest further that e expected, and even desired, such
misinterpretation.  It seems clear that Defendant believed that eir
post contained incorrect information.

Defendant cannot successfully argue that e was not aware of the
differing truth of the matter, because e was necessarily aware of the
exact nature of the changes as Contestmaster of Morendil's Feline
Orphanage.  CFJ 827 established that the failure to disclaim a post as
containing possibly incorrect information lends a presumption of
correctness to the contents of that message, so there is no defense on
the claim that the information was not presented as correct.

Rule 1497/3 prescribes that any Player who presents as correct
information which e believes to be incorrect as part of any message
sent to the Public Forum [...] commits the Crime of Misrepresentation,
a Class C Crime.  It is therefore Petitioner's allegation that
Defendant did commit the Crime of Misrepresentation by eir post.
Petitioner prays that the Court, in accordance with the Rules and the
principles of Justice, find the Defendant guilty of this Crime and
impose the appropriate punishment.

I affirm that the abovegoing statements and representations are true.

Kelly Martin
29 April 1996

